## What NOT to edit

If this repo consumes synced files from an upstream (check for `.github/workflows/sync-from-upstream.yml`), those files are overwritten on every sync — local edits are lost. The list below is a starting set; the canonical list lives in the upstream's sync manifest, not in your consumer repo. Adjust the entries below to match what your sync workflow actually pulls.

Common synced surfaces:

- `.codex/skills/**`
- `.codex/references/roles/**`
- `.codex/REVIEW_WORKFLOW.md`
- `.codex/settings.json`
- `.github/copilot-instructions.md`

If your issue requires changing any of these, **stop and post a comment on the issue** explaining the change belongs upstream. Don't edit the consumer copy — it'll be reverted on the next sync.

## Filesystem hygiene

- Use repo-scoped `/tmp` paths: `/tmp/<repo-name>/...` rather than bare `/tmp/foo` to avoid collisions across parallel sessions on the same machine.

## Out-of-scope guardrails

If you discover any of these mid-issue, **stop, comment on the issue, classify the bail (see _§ Continuous improvement — classify every bail_ below), and exit without a PR**:

- **Issue title starts with `Epic:` or otherwise reads as cross-repo coordination work.** Epics are tracking issues, not bounded implementation tasks; bail after reading the title.
- The issue requires touching another repository (cross-repo coordination).
- The issue is "submit a form to a regulator," "procure a certificate," "rotate a production secret," or any other action whose deliverable is a signed PDF, an email to a government mailbox, or a Vault/secret-store mutation — not code. A short comment back is enough.
- The issue has open policy questions — re-read the body; if it asks "should we A or B?" or "decision needed," that's a human call.
- The issue requires deleting org-level secrets, modifying branch protection, or installing GitHub Apps — these have organization-wide blast radius and need human verification.
- Acceptance criteria can't be satisfied without changing the synced surfaces listed above.
- **Your branch's diff vs the current integration branch shows large DELETIONS in files you didn't author.** This is the stacked-PR-revert trap: a sibling iteration's PR merged mid-loop, and your branch's baseline now predates it, so opening this PR would _revert_ the sibling's work. Comment on the issue noting the sibling-merge race and exit — the human can re-run after the dust settles.

## Continuous improvement — classify every bail

This loop pairs with the **`/backlog-refinement`** skill to form a learning system: refinement curates the `dev: agent` queue you pull from, and **every bail teaches the system where the backlog or the loop fell short.** The shared rubric is `.codex/skills/backlog-refinement/RUBRIC.md` (§3 lists the `agent-bail:` taxonomy; §4 is this protocol). So when you exit _without a PR_, do not just comment and leave — before exiting:

1. **Read `RUBRIC.md` §3 and pick the dominant `agent-bail:` category** for why you're bailing (one label; mention secondary reasons in your comment). Use the category's current bucket and preventability classification from the consumer-owned rubric; do not rely on a copied taxonomy in this file.
2. **Relabel:** `gh issue edit <N> --add-label "agent-bail: <category>" --add-label "agent: refined" --remove-label "dev: agent"`. (Removing `dev: agent` stops the loop re-picking it; the removal is itself a high-signal RCA trigger — it means refinement passed something the loop couldn't finish.)
3. **End your issue comment with the RCA stub** so the post-run `/backlog-refinement rca` pass can aggregate it. Answer the two questions honestly — _what could have made automation succeed here_, and if nothing, _what shape should refinement learn to exclude_:

   ```
   <!-- agent-loop-rca
   category: <agent-bail category>
   bucket: A|B
   preventable: yes|no
   what-could-differ: <one line — the answer, or "nothing: inherent">
   rubric-impact: <which RUBRIC §2 transformation or §3 disqualifier this sharpens>
   -->
   ```

If `/backlog-refinement` isn't installed in this repo, still comment and exit; skip the rubric lookup and relabel rather than inventing a category.

## Pre-push checks

**Don't try to invoke `refactorpass`, `grill`, `deepgrill`, or `reviewit` from this script.** Skills don't reliably auto-activate in a one-shot non-interactive worker when they are merely mentioned as optional. Until the loop invokes them deterministically, leave the pre-push refactor pass and post-push reviewer chain to the human operator.

Do **shell-level** checks instead — they work in non-interactive mode. Substitute the actual commands from your "Build / test" section above:

```bash
<typecheck command>           # whole repo, fast
<test command, scoped>        # only the area you touched
<lint command>                # auto-fix what's fixable; verify nothing complains after
```

A green diff against typecheck + targeted test + lint is a much stronger ship-readiness signal than a skill that never activated.

## Pre-PR sanity check (CRITICAL)

Before opening the PR, run this and read it:

```bash
git diff --stat origin/<integration-branch>..HEAD | tail -3
git log --oneline origin/<integration-branch>..HEAD
```

Two failure modes to catch here:

1. **Reverting another iteration's work.** If the diffstat shows DELETIONS in files you didn't touch (the bullet in the guardrail section above), your branch's baseline predates a sibling iteration's merge. Stop.
2. **Cross-cutting scope from prior iterations.** If `git log` shows commits you didn't author (typically merges from the agent-loop collection branch), your PR's diff vs the configured integration branch will include their work. Don't pretend it's your issue's scope — call it out in the PR body's "Also in this PR" section (template below). A narrowly titled PR that quietly ships an unrelated production change is a review-trust violation.

## PR shape

```markdown
## Summary

<1–3 bullets, what changed and why — scoped to YOUR assigned issue>

## Also in this PR (cross-cutting scope)

<Only include this section if `git log origin/<integration-branch>..HEAD` shows commits
you didn't author — i.e., your branch carried prior-iteration content
forward via the agent-loop collection branch. List each cross-cutting
change with the issue it closes, so reviewers see the full scope.>

- **<area> — <one-line summary>** (`path/to/main/file.ts`): <why>.
  Closes #<other-issue>.

## Test plan

- [ ] <typecheck command>
- [ ] <test command, scoped>
- [ ] <lint command>
- [ ] <issue-specific verification>

## Agent-loop context

This PR is iteration <N> of an agent-loop run on collection branch
`<branch-name>`. A summary PR will be opened at the end of the run
consolidating all iterations — recommended merge unit is the summary
PR; merging this per-issue PR in isolation risks the stacked-PR-revert
trap once siblings merge.

Closes #<N>
```

**PR title honesty.** The title must match the BIGGEST scope item in the diff, not just your assigned issue. If the diff carries an unrelated change from a prior iteration alongside your issue's work, prefer a neutral title (`chore: agent-loop iteration N — <areas>`) or a multi-area conventional commit (`feat(backend,mobile): …`). A title that lies about scope wastes reviewer time and almost always triggers AI-reviewer findings about "PR description focuses on X but introduces Y."

**Do not run `/reviewit` yourself.** The human will trigger `/reviewit <pr-number>` on whichever PR they want reviewed (usually the summary PR for a bundled run, not the per-issue PRs).

